text: It is an important indicator that the Russian army is exhausted and has recognized its inability to defeat Ukraine. I do not believe that situation will significantly change with mobilization. 2/10
context_annotations: [{"domain": {"id": "123", "name": "Ongoing News Story", "description": "Ongoing News Stories like 'Brexit'"}, "entity": {"id": "1484601166080081920", "name": "Russo-Ukrainian conflict"}}]

text: Secondly, personnel is only a part of the capability structure, and Russia has problems with all components of capability‚Äîdoctrine, organization, leadership, and weapons. Russia severely lacks experienced battlefield officers. It also struggles with delivering new weapons. 5/10
context_annotations: [{"domain": {"id": "123", "name": "Ongoing News Story", "description": "Ongoing News Stories like 'Brexit'"}, "entity": {"id": "1484601166080081920", "name": "Russo-Ukrainian conflict"}}]

text: Finally, mobilization is going to be very unpopular in Russia. The government plans to push the ‚Äúdefensive war‚Äù narrative with its propaganda. It will advertise the idea of defending Russia from NATO. 6/10

text: The problem is that Russians do not perceive newly occupied regions of Ukraine as Russia, and the motivation to die for recently annexed regions will be very low. If Russia annexes new regions, that will not stop Ukraine from taking them back. 7/10

in Ukraine", "description": "Russian President Vladimir Putin and US President Joe Biden spoke again on the phone Thursday afternoon about Ukraine. Russia requested the call, according to The New York Times. Per the White House, Putin and Biden spoke for about 50 minutes. The leaders last call that was made known to the public was on December 7, when Russia said it would send ideas on the crisis to Washington "within a week," Reuters reported. The US Air Force flew two reconnaissance missions over eastern Ukraine this week, the first on December 27 just a few days after Russia said it would withdraw 10,000 troops from the shared border, CNN reported.

More on the leaders’ call:
- Ukraine has been a point of contention for the two countries since the annexation of Crimea in 2014, Al Jazeera reports

- Russia denied a new assault on Ukraine during the previous conversation and warned against any NATO military involvement, according to Reuters and Al Jazeera

- Biden warned Putin about possible sanctions against Russia in case of an escalation during the December 7 call, AFP reports"}}, {"domain": {"id": "29", "name": "Events [Entity Service]", "description": "Entity Service related Events domain"}, "entity": {"id": "1505769604353703937", "name": "US President Biden, Polish President Duda receive humanitarian briefing on Ukraine", "description": "US President Joe Biden landed in Poland on Friday, where he received a briefing on the humanitarian situation in Ukraine alongside Polish President Andrzej Duda. text:
Putin's mobilisation looks asymmetrical:

1. Partial mobilisation in large cities, especially soft in Moscow & Petersburg
2. Total mobilisation in remote rural regions, especially ethnic ones

We don't have hard data yet, this mobilisation may include elements of ethnic cleansing https://t.co/63YAMM2kei

in Ukraine", "description": "Russian President Vladimir Putin and US President Joe Biden spoke again on the phone Thursday afternoon about Ukraine. Russia requested the call, according to The New York Times. Per the White House, Putin and Biden spoke for about 50 minutes. The leaders last call that was made known to the public was on December 7, when Russia said it would send ideas on the crisis to Washington "within a week," Reuters reported. The US Air Force flew two reconnaissance missions over eastern Ukraine this week, the first on December 27 just a few days after Russia said it would withdraw 10,000 troops from the shared border, CNN reported.

More on the leaders’ call:
- Ukraine has been a point of contention for the two countries since the annexation of Crimea in 2014, Al Jazeera reports

- Russia denied a new assault on Ukraine during the previous conversation and warned against any NATO military involvement, according to Reuters and Al Jazeera
